00:56:30,078 --> 00:56:33,247
The year after that, he did them all...

729
00:56:33,248 --> 00:56:35,628
including the Warden's.

730
00:56:36,709 --> 00:56:40,546
The year after that, they rescheduled the start of the intramural season

731
00:56:40,547 --> 00:56:43,227
to coincide with tax season.

732
00:56:44,926 --> 00:56:49,221
The guards on the opposing teams all remembered to bring their W-2s.

733
00:56:49,222 --> 00:56:53,433
So, Moresby Prison issued you your gun, but you had to pay for it?

734
00:56:53,434 --> 00:56:55,269
Damn right. The holster, too.

735
00:56:55,270 --> 00:56:56,603
That's tax-deductible.

736
00:56:56,604 --> 00:56:57,854
You can write that off.

737
00:56:57,855 --> 00:57:01,275
yes, sir. andy was a regular cottage industry.

738
00:57:01,276 --> 00:57:04,403
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

739
00:57:04,404 --> 00:57:06,530
he was allowed a staff.

740
00:57:06,531 --> 00:57:09,074
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

741
00:57:09,075 --> 00:57:11,827
It got me out of the wood shop a month out of the year,

742
00:57:11,828 --> 00:57:14,268
and that was fine by me.

743
00:57:26,467 --> 00:57:28,187
(Men shouting) 

744
00:57:33,623 --> 00:57:34,891
Knock it off. And still...he kept sending those letters. Red, Andy. It's Brooks. watch the door. Please, Brooks. - Just calm the fuck down. - Stay back! - Stay back! - What the hell's going on?

745
00:57:34,892 --> 00:57:38,061
You tell me. One second he's fine. Then out comes the knife.

746
00:57:38,062 --> 00:57:40,606
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

747
00:57:40,607 --> 00:57:42,816
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

748
00:57:42,817 --> 00:57:44,610
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

749
00:57:44,611 --> 00:57:46,570
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

750
00:57:46,571 --> 00:57:48,771
It's what they done!

751
00:57:48,781 --> 00:57:50,282
I...I got no choice...

752
00:57:50,283 --> 00:57:53,035
You're not gonna hurt him. Even Heywood knows that.

753
00:57:53,036 --> 00:57:55,746
- Right, Heywood? - I...I know that, sure.

754
00:57:55,747 --> 00:57:59,249
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend, and you're a reasonable man.

755
00:57:59,250 --> 00:58:00,626
That's right. Right, guys?

756
00:58:00,627 --> 00:58:04,087
- Yes. - So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

757
00:58:04,088 --> 00:58:06,228
Put the knife down.

758
00:58:13,014 --> 00:58:14,794
(Heywood gasps) 

759
00:58:22,574 --> 00:58:29,574
(Brooks sobs) [SOBBING] Shit. Brooks... Look at his neck, for God's sake. Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding. It's the only... It's the only way they'd let me stay. Come on. This is crazy. You don't want to do this. Put it down.

760
00:58:30,365 --> 00:58:34,485
Come on. Take it easy. You're going to be all right.

761
00:58:35,161 --> 00:58:36,401
him?

762
00:58:36,621 --> 00:58:40,374
Hell, what about me? Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

763
00:58:40,375 --> 00:58:43,085
shit, heywood, you've had worse from shaving.

764
00:58:43,086 --> 00:58:45,420
What the hell did you do to set him off, anyway?

765
00:58:45,421 --> 00:58:47,839
Nothing. I come in here to say fare-thee-well.

766
00:58:47,840 --> 00:58:51,420
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

767
00:58:53,012 --> 00:58:56,223
I just don't understand what happened in there. That's all.

768
00:58:56,224 --> 00:58:58,892
The old man's as crazy as a rat in a tin shithouse.

769
00:58:58,893 --> 00:59:01,186
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

770
00:59:01,187 --> 00:59:04,272
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants. - Fuck you!

771
00:59:04,273 --> 00:59:05,732
Would you knock it off?

772
00:59:05,733 --> 00:59:07,933
Brooks ain't no bug.

773
00:59:08,152 --> 00:59:09,872
He's just...

774
00:59:11,906 --> 00:59:14,586
He's just institutionalized.

775
00:59:15,076 --> 00:59:16,827
Institutionalized, my ass.

776
00:59:16,828 --> 00:59:20,888
The man's been in here 50 years, Heywood. 50 years.

777
00:59:21,207 --> 00:59:22,999
This is all he knows.

778
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:25,502
In here, he's an important man.

779
00:59:25,503 --> 00:59:27,045
He's an educated man.

780
00:59:27,046 --> 00:59:29,366
Outside, he's nothing.

781
00:59:31,300 --> 00:59:34,010
Just a used-up con with arthritis in both hands.

782
00:59:34,011 --> 00:59:37,305
Probably couldn't get a library card if he tried.

783
00:59:37,306 --> 00:59:39,474
You know what I'm trying to say?

784
00:59:39,475 --> 00:59:43,415
Red, I do believe you're talking out of your ass.

785
00:59:43,479 --> 00:59:46,398
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

786
00:59:46,399 --> 00:59:49,979
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

787
00:59:50,361 --> 00:59:52,621
First you hate 'em...

788
00:59:53,990 --> 00:59:56,610
..then you get used to 'em.

789
00:59:57,702 --> 00:59:59,962
Enough time passes...

790
01:00:00,413 --> 01:00:03,153
you get so you depend on 'em.

791
01:00:03,458 --> 01:00:05,876
That's institutionalized.

792
01:00:05,877 --> 01:00:07,177
shit.

793
01:00:07,253 --> 01:00:08,962
You can never get like that.

794
01:00:08,963 --> 01:00:10,503
Oh, yeah?

795
01:00:10,965 --> 01:00:13,633
Say that when you've been here as long as Brooks has.

796
01:00:13,634 --> 01:00:15,474
Goddamn right.

797
01:00:17,847 --> 01:00:20,474
They send you here for life.

798
01:00:20,475 --> 01:00:23,275
That's exactly what they take.

799
01:00:24,479 --> 01:00:27,219
The part that counts, anyway.

800
01:00:28,193 --> 01:00:29,913
(Jake screeches) [JAKE CROWING] 

801
01:00:34,071 --> 01:00:37,411
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

802
01:00:38,159 --> 01:00:40,059
You go on, now.

803
01:00:41,078 --> 01:00:42,798
You're free.

804
01:01:01,641 --> 01:01:02,881
Bye.

805
01:01:04,602 --> 01:01:06,682
Good luck, Brooks.

806
01:01:43,099 --> 01:01:44,939
dear fellas...

807
01:01:45,893 --> 01:01:50,013
I can't believe how fast things move on the outside.

808
01:01:50,189 --> 01:01:51,849
(Horn blares) 

809
01:01:51,524 --> 01:01:54,651
Watch it, old-timer! Are you trying to get killed?

810
01:01:54,652 --> 01:01:58,071
I saw an automobile once, when I was a kid,

811
01:01:58,072 --> 01:02:00,812
but now...they're everywhere.

812
01:02:05,204 --> 01:02:09,204
The world went and got itself in a big damn hurry.

813
01:02:25,141 --> 01:02:30,101
The parole board got me into this halfway house called The Brewer,

814
01:02:31,522 --> 01:02:35,102
and a job bagging groceries at the Foodway.

815
01:02:37,361 --> 01:02:42,741
It's hard work, and I try to keep up, but my hands hurt most of the time.

816
01:02:42,783 --> 01:02:44,868
make sure your man double-bags.

817
01:02:44,869 --> 01:02:47,203
Last time, the bottom near came out.

818
01:02:47,204 --> 01:02:50,582
Make sure you double-bag, like the lady says. Understand?

819
01:02:50,583 --> 01:02:52,125
Yes, sir. I surely will.

820
01:02:52,126 --> 01:02:56,186
i don't think the store manager likes me very much.

821
01:02:56,005 --> 01:02:57,845
(Pigeons cooing) 

822
01:02:58,883 --> 01:03:03,423
Sometimes, after work, I go to the park and feed the birds.

823
01:03:03,763 --> 01:03:08,003
I keep thinking Jake might just show up and say hello.

824
01:04:30,975 --> 01:04:32,455
(Scraping) 

825
01:07:45,963 --> 01:07:50,263
[ARIA FROM THE MARRIAGE OF FIGARO PLAYS ON RECORD PLAYER] 

826
01:08:12,071 --> 01:08:13,671
(Locks door) 

827
01:08:32,593 --> 01:08:34,193
(Feedback hisses) [SCREECHING] 

828
01:08:35,928 --> 01:08:38,308
(Music over loudspeakers) 

829
01:08:42,851 --> 01:08:44,691
(Aria continues) 

830
01:09:07,753 --> 01:09:09,233
(Banging at door) [KNOCKING] 

831
01:09:46,433 --> 01:09:49,773
like he said. I've got to pinch a loaf.

832
01:09:58,969 --> 01:03:33,334
like he said. I've got to pinch a loaf. Wow.

833
01:03:33,335 --> 01:03:35,460
like he said. I've got to pinch a loaf. ...like he said. But he never does. And I hope, wherever he is, he's doing OK and making new friends. I have trouble sleeping at night. I have bad dreams, like I'm falling. I wake up, scared. Sometimes it takes me a while to remember where I am.

834
01:03:35,461 --> 01:03:37,003
Maybe I should get me a gun

835
01:03:37,004 --> 01:03:40,644
and rob the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

836
01:03:40,967 --> 01:03:43,385
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

837
01:03:43,386 --> 01:03:45,646
Sort of like a bonus.

838
01:03:46,847 --> 01:03:51,147
I guess I'm too old for that sort of nonsense any more.

839
01:03:51,185 --> 01:03:53,311
I don't like it here.

840
01:03:53,312 --> 01:03:56,064
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

841
01:03:56,065 --> 01:03:57,232
I've decided...

842
01:03:57,233 --> 01:03:58,953
not to stay.

843
01:04:10,454 --> 01:04:13,434
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.

844
01:04:14,041 --> 01:04:16,781
Not for an old crook like me.

845
01:05:19,148 --> 01:05:23,928
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss. Not for an old crook like me.

846
01:05:24,361 --> 01:05:28,406
PS. Tell Heywood I'm sorry I put a knife to his throat.

847
01:05:28,407 --> 01:05:30,907
No hard feelings. Brooks.

848
01:05:41,212 --> 01:05:43,892
He should have died in here.

849
01:05:48,719 --> 01:05:53,859
what the fuck have you done? it's a goddamn mess. i'll tell you that.

850
01:05:57,895 --> 01:05:59,395
What's all this?

851
01:05:59,396 --> 01:06:03,358
You tell me, fuck-stick. They're all addressed to you.

852
01:06:03,359 --> 01:06:04,839
Take it.

853
01:06:13,619 --> 01:06:15,819
Dear Mr. Dufresne...

854
01:06:16,288 --> 01:06:18,373
In response to your repeated enquiries,

855
01:06:18,374 --> 01:06:23,169
the State has allocated the enclosed funds for your library project.

856
01:06:23,170 --> 01:06:25,370
This is 200 dollars.

857
01:06:25,589 --> 01:06:29,592
In addition, the Library District has generously responded

858
01:06:29,593 --> 01:06:32,387
with a charitable donation of used books and sundries.

859
01:06:32,388 --> 01:06:34,556
We trust this will fill your needs.

860
01:06:34,557 --> 01:06:38,768
We now consider the matter closed. Please stop sending us letters.

861
01:06:38,769 --> 01:06:41,688
I want all this cleared out before the Warden gets back.

862
01:06:41,689 --> 01:06:43,229
Yes, sir.

863
01:06:47,111 --> 01:06:49,251
Good for you, Andy.

864
01:06:51,115 --> 01:06:52,355
Wow!

865
01:06:53,659 --> 01:06:56,039
It only took six years.

866
01:06:57,037 --> 01:06:59,998
From now on, I'll write two letters a week, instead of one.

867
01:06:59,999 --> 01:07:03,626
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough. You'd better get all this stuff out,

868
01:07:03,627 --> 01:07:04,878
like the Captain said.

869
01:07:04,879 --> 01:07:10,319
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf. When I come back, this is all gone, right?

870
01:07:14,930 --> 01:07:16,170
Wow.

871
01:07:47,004 --> 01:07:50,764
♪ MOZART: Duettino from The Marriage Of Figaro

872
01:07:51,175 --> 01:07:53,015
♪ Sull'aria...

873
01:07:57,389 --> 01:07:58,473
Andy,

874
01:07:58,474 --> 01:07:59,891
do you hear that?

875
01:07:59,892 --> 01:08:01,732
♪ ..zeffiretto

876
01:08:15,824 --> 01:08:18,084
♪ Questa sera spirera

877
01:08:54,071 --> 01:08:55,911
♪ Sotto i pini

878
01:09:17,707 --> 01:09:20,680
Forget? ♪ Del boschetto ♪ Sotto i pini... dufresne? Dufresne? Andy, let me out. Andy?

879
01:09:20,681 --> 01:09:25,935
i have no idea to this day what those two italian ladies were singing about.

880
01:09:25,936 --> 01:09:28,438
The truth is, I don't want to know.

881
01:09:28,439 --> 01:09:31,419
Some things are best left unsaid.

882
01:09:34,570 --> 01:09:39,699
I like to think they were singing about something so beautiful, it can't be expressed in words...

883
01:09:39,700 --> 01:09:43,100
and makes your heart ache because of it.

884
01:09:44,288 --> 01:09:47,081
I tell you, those voices soared...

885
01:09:47,082 --> 01:09:51,711
higher and farther than anybody in a grey place dares to dream.

886
01:09:51,712 --> 01:09:55,173
It was like some beautiful bird flapped into our drab little cage

887
01:09:55,174 --> 01:09:58,274
and made those walls dissolve away.

888
01:09:58,385 --> 01:10:00,803
And for the briefest of moments...

889
01:10:00,804 --> 01:10:04,084
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

890
01:10:06,393 --> 01:10:09,853
It pissed the Warden off something awful.

891
01:10:10,314 --> 01:10:12,154
Open the door.

892
01:10:14,193 --> 01:10:15,853
Open it up!

893
01:10:17,321 --> 01:10:19,821
Dufresne, open this door!

894
01:10:19,782 --> 01:10:21,382
(Bangs door) 

895
01:10:21,325 --> 01:10:23,165
(Bangs door) Turn that off!

896
01:10:26,497 --> 01:10:28,337
(Aria continues) 

897
01:10:29,458 --> 01:10:32,978
I am warning you, Dufresne. Turn that off!

898
01:10:35,714 --> 01:10:37,674
(Increases volume) 

899
01:10:46,058 --> 01:10:47,718
Dufresne...

900
01:10:49,061 --> 01:10:51,021
You're mine now.

901
01:10:58,695 --> 01:11:01,531
andy got two weeks in the hole for that little stunt.

902
01:11:01,532 --> 01:11:03,312
(Hadley stops record) on your feet!

903
01:11:05,160 --> 01:11:08,200
- Hey, look who's here. - Maestro!

904
01:11:08,747 --> 01:11:12,875
Y-Y-You couldn't play something good, huh? Hank Williams or something?

905
01:11:12,876 --> 01:11:15,628
They broke the door down before I could take requests.

906
01:11:15,629 --> 01:11:17,505
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

907
01:11:17,506 --> 01:11:18,840
Easiest time I ever did.

908
01:11:18,841 --> 01:11:21,884
Bullshit! There's no such thing as easy time in the hole.

909
01:11:21,885 --> 01:11:24,595
A week in the hole is like a year.

910
01:11:24,596 --> 01:11:27,390
I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

911
01:11:27,391 --> 01:11:31,811
So, they let you tote that record player down there, huh?

912
01:11:32,855 --> 01:11:34,755
It was in here.

913
01:11:57,237 --> 01:11:57,753
You going to play it? You going to play it? You going to play it? And in here. That's the beauty of music. They can't get that from you. Haven't you ever felt that way about music? Well, I played a mean harmonica, as a younger man. Lost interest in it, though. Didn't make much sense in here.

914
01:11:57,754 --> 01:12:00,298
Here's where it makes the most sense.

915
01:12:00,299 --> 01:12:02,967
You need it, so you don't forget.

916
01:12:02,968 --> 01:12:04,385
Forget?

917
01:12:04,386 --> 01:12:06,226
Forget that...

918
01:12:06,430 --> 01:12:08,570
there are places...

919
01:12:09,850 --> 01:12:12,477
..in the world that aren't made out of stone...

920
01:12:12,478 --> 01:12:14,498
that there's a...

921
01:12:14,605 --> 01:12:16,522
there's something...

922
01:12:16,523 --> 01:12:19,400
inside that they can't get to...

923
01:12:19,401 --> 01:12:21,721
that they can't touch.

924
01:12:21,778 --> 01:12:23,438
It's yours.

925
01:12:25,073 --> 01:12:27,693
What are you talking about?

926
01:12:27,868 --> 01:12:29,168
Hope.

927
01:12:29,536 --> 01:12:30,836
Hope?

928
01:12:33,248 --> 01:12:36,000
Let me tell you something, my friend.

929
01:12:36,001 --> 01:12:38,561
Hope is a dangerous thing.

930
01:12:39,546 --> 01:12:42,226
Hope can drive a man insane.

931
01:12:42,633 --> 01:12:44,634
It's got no use on the inside.

932
01:12:44,635 --> 01:12:47,735
You'd better get used to that idea.

933
01:12:49,723 --> 01:12:51,683
Like Brooks did?

934
01:13:16,583 --> 01:13:18,123
Sit down.

935
01:13:22,839 --> 01:13:26,384
It says here that you've served 30 years of a life sentence.

936
01:13:26,385 --> 01:13:29,095
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

937
01:13:29,096 --> 01:13:30,876
Oh, yes, sir.

938
01:13:31,181 --> 01:13:33,141
Without a doubt.

939
01:13:34,309 --> 01:13:37,769
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

940
01:13:39,231 --> 01:13:41,357
No danger to society here.

941
01:13:41,358 --> 01:13:43,498
God's honest truth.

942
01:13:45,779 --> 01:13:48,279
Absolutely rehabilitated.

943
01:13:57,791 --> 01:13:59,331
30 years.

944
01:14:00,961 --> 01:14:03,087
Jesus, when they say it like that...

945
01:14:03,088 --> 01:14:05,588
You wonder where it went.

946
01:14:08,135 --> 01:14:10,935
I wonder where ten years went.

947
01:14:15,267 --> 01:14:16,567
Here.

948
01:14:16,643 --> 01:14:19,563
Little parole rejection present.

949
01:14:20,647 --> 01:14:22,773
Go ahead and open it.

950
01:14:22,774 --> 01:14:26,652
I had to go through one of your competitors. I hope you don't mind.

951
01:14:26,653 --> 01:14:29,393
I wanted it to be a surprise.

952
01:14:38,874 --> 01:14:41,254
It's very pretty, Andy.

953
01:14:42,044 --> 01:14:43,644
Thank you.

954
01:14:45,881 --> 01:14:48,381
Are you going to play it?

955
01:14:52,095 --> 01:14:53,275
No.

956
01:14:56,475 --> 01:14:58,315
Not right now.

957
01:15:04,068 --> 01:15:06,748
(Guards shout) [GUARDS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY] 

958
01:15:05,817 --> 01:15:08,017
Tier 3 South. Clear.

959
01:15:08,945 --> 01:15:11,072
Tier 4 North. Clear.

960
01:15:11,073 --> 01:15:13,273
Tier 1 South. Clear.

961
01:15:15,994 --> 01:15:17,474
Fall in!

962
01:15:20,791 --> 01:15:22,451
(Gate buzzer) 

963
01:15:50,529 --> 01:15:52,549
(Guard's footsteps) 

964
01:15:52,656 --> 01:15:54,316
(Click of light switches) Lights out!

965
01:16:01,248 --> 01:16:03,208
(Guard walks away) 

966
01:16:09,506 --> 01:16:11,526
(Outer door closes) 

967
01:16:20,434 --> 01:16:22,694
(Gently plays one note) 

968
01:16:27,941 --> 01:16:29,481
(Hammering) 

969
01:16:29,151 --> 01:16:31,277
andy was as good as his word.

970
01:16:31,278 --> 01:16:34,858
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

971
01:16:36,408 --> 01:16:40,588
In 1959, the State Senate finally clued into the fact

972
01:16:40,620 --> 01:16:43,581
they couldn't buy him off with just a $200 check.

973
01:16:43,582 --> 01:16:49,202
Appropriations Committee voted an annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.

974
01:16:50,255 --> 01:16:52,047
And you'd be amazed

975
01:16:52,048 --> 01:16:53,799
how far Andy could stretch it.

976
01:16:53,800 --> 01:16:56,761
He made deals with book clubs, charity groups.

977
01:16:56,762 --> 01:16:59,221
He bought remaindered books by the pound.

978
01:16:59,222 --> 01:17:01,182
Treasure Island.

979
