01:52:18,590 --> 01:52:20,799
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1468
01:52:20,800 --> 01:52:22,426
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1469
01:52:22,427 --> 01:52:24,761
Don't say that to me again.

1470
01:52:24,762 --> 01:52:25,929
But, sir, he wasn't.

1471
01:52:25,930 --> 01:52:28,181
I can see that, Haig!

1472
01:52:28,182 --> 01:52:29,975
You think I'm blind?

1473
01:52:29,976 --> 01:52:33,186
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1474
01:52:33,187 --> 01:52:34,271
No, sir.

1475
01:52:34,272 --> 01:52:36,172
What about you?

1476
01:52:36,399 --> 01:52:38,239
Are you blind?

1477
01:52:38,318 --> 01:52:40,944
- Tell me what this is. - Last night's count.

1478
01:52:40,945 --> 01:52:44,323
You see Dufresne's name there? I sure do. See? Right there.

1479
01:52:44,324 --> 01:52:45,864
Dufresne.

1480
01:52:47,452 --> 01:52:50,432
He was in his cell at lights out.

1481
01:53:06,212 --> 01:53:07,220
The next morning, right about the time Raquel was spilling her secret... The next morning, right about the time Raquel was spilling her secret... It stands to reason he'd still be here in the morning. I want him found. Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now! Yes, sir! Let's go, let's go! Move your butts! Move it!

1482
01:53:07,221 --> 01:53:08,581
Stand.

1483
01:53:09,390 --> 01:53:10,690
Well?

1484
01:53:14,020 --> 01:53:15,228
Well, what?

1485
01:53:15,229 --> 01:53:19,733
I see you two all the time. You're thick as thieves, you are.

1486
01:53:19,734 --> 01:53:21,443
He must have said something.

1487
01:53:21,444 --> 01:53:23,404
No, sir, Warden.

1488
01:53:23,571 --> 01:53:25,231
Not a word.

1489
01:53:27,033 --> 01:53:29,293
Lord, it's a miracle!

1490
01:53:30,078 --> 01:53:32,621
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1491
01:53:32,622 --> 01:53:34,456
Nothing left but...

1492
01:53:34,457 --> 01:53:37,377
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1493
01:53:37,460 --> 01:53:39,294
And that cupcake on the wall.

1494
01:53:39,295 --> 01:53:41,004
Let's ask her.

1495
01:53:41,005 --> 01:53:46,025
Maybe she knows. What say there, Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1496
01:53:46,052 --> 01:53:47,135
Ah...

1497
01:53:47,136 --> 01:53:48,679
I guess not.

1498
01:53:48,680 --> 01:53:51,600
Why should she be any different?

1499
01:53:51,641 --> 01:53:53,901
This is a conspiracy.

1500
01:53:54,185 --> 01:53:56,385
That's what this is.

1501
01:53:56,479 --> 01:53:58,079
One big...

1502
01:53:58,106 --> 01:54:00,066
damn conspiracy!

1503
01:54:00,942 --> 01:54:03,382
And everyone's in on it!

1504
01:54:03,695 --> 01:54:05,535
Including her!

1505
01:54:06,322 --> 01:54:07,922
(Clattering) 

1506
01:54:31,764 --> 01:54:33,484
(Sirens blare) 

1507
01:54:39,647 --> 01:54:41,127
in 1966,

1508
01:54:41,607 --> 01:54:43,867
Andy Dufresne escaped

1509
01:54:44,360 --> 01:54:46,680
from Shawshank Prison.

1510
01:54:48,114 --> 01:54:50,949
All they found of him was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1511
01:54:50,950 --> 01:54:52,730
a bar of soap

1512
01:54:53,077 --> 01:54:57,317
and an old rock hammer damn near worn down to the nub.

1513
01:55:01,836 --> 01:55:06,757
I remember thinking it would take a man 600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1514
01:55:06,758 --> 01:55:09,678
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1515
01:55:28,029 --> 01:55:30,409
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1516
01:55:31,157 --> 01:55:34,743
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1517
01:55:34,744 --> 01:55:36,704
An Ice Age here,

1518
01:55:37,121 --> 01:55:40,701
a million years of mountain-building there.

1519
01:55:40,750 --> 01:55:44,270
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1520
01:55:44,378 --> 01:55:47,058
That's all it takes, really.

1521
01:55:54,975 --> 01:55:56,695
(Coughing) [MAN COUGHING] 

1522
01:55:59,023 --> 01:56:05,107
That's where Andy crossed. Pressure... and time. That and a big goddamn poster. Like I said, in prison, a man will do most anything to keep his mind occupied.

1523
01:56:05,108 --> 01:56:10,362
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1524
01:56:10,363 --> 01:56:12,563
A handful at a time.

1525
01:56:14,283 --> 01:56:16,535
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1526
01:56:16,536 --> 01:56:19,454
Andy decided he'd been here just about long enough.

1527
01:56:19,455 --> 01:56:22,495
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1528
01:56:22,959 --> 01:56:25,699
I'm just about finished, sir.

1529
01:56:46,440 --> 01:56:48,820
Three deposits tonight.

1530
01:56:55,700 --> 01:56:58,260
Andy did like he was told.

1531
01:56:58,786 --> 01:57:02,306
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1532
01:57:05,877 --> 01:57:08,003
The guard simply didn't notice.

1533
01:57:08,004 --> 01:57:09,844
Neither did I.

1534
01:57:10,131 --> 01:57:15,031
I mean, seriously, how often do you really look at a man's shoes?

1535
01:57:49,170 --> 01:57:50,830
(Thunderclap) 

1536
01:59:18,509 --> 01:59:24,849
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1537
01:59:24,765 --> 01:59:26,005
(Gags) 

1538
01:59:26,017 --> 01:59:28,817
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1539
01:59:28,102 --> 01:59:30,062
(Coughs and spits) 

1540
01:59:32,732 --> 01:59:34,332
500 yards.

1541
01:59:35,985 --> 01:59:39,505
That's the length of five football fields.

1542
01:59:39,530 --> 01:59:41,970
Just shy of half a mile.

1543
02:00:23,324 --> 02:00:24,684
(Laughs) 

1544
02:00:31,209 --> 02:00:32,689
[LAUGHING] 

1545
02:00:37,004 --> 02:00:41,633
The next morning, right about the time Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1546
02:00:41,634 --> 02:00:44,854
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1547
02:00:45,137 --> 02:00:47,639
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1548
02:00:47,640 --> 02:00:49,720
Until that moment,

1549
02:00:49,767 --> 02:00:51,726
he didn't exist,

1550
02:00:51,727 --> 02:00:53,144
except on paper.

1551
02:00:53,145 --> 02:00:54,270
May I help you?

1552
02:00:54,271 --> 02:00:56,398
he had all the proper id,

1553
02:00:56,399 --> 02:01:00,110
driver's license, birth certificate, social security card.

1554
02:01:00,111 --> 02:01:03,391
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1555
02:01:03,489 --> 02:01:06,616
I must say, I'm sorry to be losing your business.

1556
02:01:06,617 --> 02:01:08,701
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1557
02:01:08,702 --> 02:01:10,302
Thank you.

1558
02:01:10,579 --> 02:01:12,455
I'm sure I will.

1559
02:01:12,456 --> 02:01:14,666
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1560
02:01:14,667 --> 02:01:16,793
Will there be anything else?

1561
02:01:16,794 --> 02:01:17,877
Please...

1562
02:01:17,878 --> 02:01:21,047
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1563
02:01:21,048 --> 02:01:23,008
I'd be happy to.

1564
02:01:23,342 --> 02:01:25,760
- Good day, sir. - Good day.

1565
02:01:25,761 --> 02:01:31,261
mr. stevens visited nearly a dozen banks in the portland area that morning.

1566
02:01:31,725 --> 02:01:37,165
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000 of Warden Norton's money.

1567
02:01:38,274 --> 02:01:40,894
Severance pay for 19 years.

1568
02:01:40,818 --> 02:01:42,478
(Phone rings) [PHONE RINGING] 

1569
02:01:41,821 --> 02:01:43,601
[PHONE RINGING] 

1570
02:01:48,868 --> 02:01:51,968
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1571
02:01:57,712 --> 02:01:59,492
(Sirens wail) [SIREN WAILING] 

1572
02:02:30,117 --> 02:02:32,197
(Sirens approaching) 

1573
02:02:43,881 --> 02:02:46,966
Byron Hadley? You have the right to remain silent.

1574
02:02:46,967 --> 02:02:51,679
If you give up the right to remain silent, anything you say will be held against you in court.

1575
02:02:51,680 --> 02:02:53,640
i wasn't there to see it.

1576
02:02:53,641 --> 02:02:59,621
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing like a little girl when they took him away.

1577
02:03:03,943 --> 02:03:07,703
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1578
02:03:22,711 --> 02:03:24,254
(Banging on door) Samuel Norton?

1579
02:03:24,255 --> 02:03:27,835
we have a warrant for your arrest. open up.

1580
02:03:27,135 --> 02:03:28,615
[KNOCKING] 

1581
02:03:30,386 --> 02:03:31,594
Norton!

1582
02:03:31,595 --> 02:03:33,346
Open the door.

1583
02:03:33,347 --> 02:03:36,087
I'm not sure which key it is.

1584
02:03:37,977 --> 02:03:39,397
Norton!

1585
02:03:45,109 --> 02:03:48,089
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1586
02:03:58,497 --> 02:04:02,166
i like to think the last thing that went through his head,

1587
02:04:02,167 --> 02:04:03,960
other than that bullet,

1588
02:04:03,961 --> 02:04:08,921
was to wonder how the hell Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1589
02:04:09,633 --> 02:04:10,800
Carter, James...

1590
02:04:10,801 --> 02:04:14,262
not long after the warden deprived us of his company,

1591
02:04:14,263 --> 02:04:17,003
I got a postcard in the mail.

1592
02:04:18,225 --> 02:04:20,727
It was blank but the postmark said...

1593
02:04:20,728 --> 02:04:22,928
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1594
02:04:23,564 --> 02:04:25,344
Fort Hancock.

1595
02:04:25,691 --> 02:04:27,817
Right on the border.

1596
02:04:27,818 --> 02:04:29,944
That's where Andy crossed.

1597
02:04:29,945 --> 02:04:34,866
When I picture him heading south in his own car with the top down,

1598
02:04:34,867 --> 02:04:37,367
it always makes me laugh.

1599
02:04:38,370 --> 02:04:40,210
Andy Dufresne,

1600
02:04:40,497 --> 02:04:43,597
who crawled through a river of shit

1601
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,640
If you're reading this, you've gotten out...

1602
02:04:42,958 --> 02:04:46,178
and came out clean on the other side.

1603
02:04:46,253 --> 02:04:48,093
Andy Dufresne,

1604
02:04:48,380 --> 02:04:50,760
headed for the Pacific.

1605
02:04:52,885 --> 02:04:55,011
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1606
02:04:55,012 --> 02:04:59,307
And he says, I believe this boy's about to have himself an accident.

1607
02:04:59,308 --> 02:05:02,560
those of us who knew him best talk about him often.

1608
02:05:02,561 --> 02:05:04,896
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1609
02:05:04,897 --> 02:05:07,482
These friends of mine could use a couple of beers!

1610
02:05:07,483 --> 02:05:10,463
- And he got it. - And he got it!

1611
02:05:10,736 --> 02:05:13,196
sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1612
02:05:13,197 --> 02:05:15,157
Andy being gone.

1613
02:05:15,324 --> 02:05:20,224
I have to remind myself that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1614
02:05:20,412 --> 02:05:23,512
Their feathers are just too bright.

1615
02:05:24,041 --> 02:05:26,167
And when they fly away,

1616
02:05:26,168 --> 02:05:31,308
the part of you that knows it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1617
02:05:31,840 --> 02:05:33,383
But still...

1618
02:05:33,384 --> 02:05:38,764
the place you live in is that much more drab and empty that they're gone.

1619
02:05:42,101 --> 02:05:44,901
I guess I just miss my friend.

1620
02:06:08,335 --> 02:06:10,295
Please sit down.

1621
02:06:15,801 --> 02:06:17,941
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1622
02:06:18,011 --> 02:06:21,472
Your files say you've served 40 years of a life sentence.

1623
02:06:21,473 --> 02:06:24,753
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1624
02:06:25,978 --> 02:06:27,818
Rehabilitated?

1625
02:06:29,606 --> 02:06:31,926
Well, now, let me see.

1626
02:06:32,735 --> 02:06:36,615
You know, I don't have any idea what that means.

1627
02:06:36,864 --> 02:06:39,490
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1628
02:06:39,491 --> 02:06:42,771
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1629
02:06:44,413 --> 02:06:47,333
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1630
02:06:47,541 --> 02:06:49,876
A politician's word so that...

1631
02:06:49,877 --> 02:06:54,957
young fellas like yourself can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1632
02:06:57,801 --> 02:07:00,721
What do you really want to know?

1633
02:07:01,054 --> 02:07:03,055
Am I sorry for what I did?

1634
02:07:03,056 --> 02:07:04,896
Well, are you?

1635
02:07:06,393 --> 02:07:10,153
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1636
02:07:10,564 --> 02:07:14,804
Not because I'm in here or because you think I should.

1637
02:07:17,488 --> 02:07:20,528
I look back on the way I was then.

1638
02:07:22,159 --> 02:07:23,759
A young...

1639
02:07:24,286 --> 02:07:27,986
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1640
02:07:31,210 --> 02:07:33,410
I wanna talk to him.

1641
02:07:34,671 --> 02:07:37,882
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1642
02:07:37,883 --> 02:07:40,563
tell him the way things are.

1643
02:07:42,137 --> 02:07:43,857
But I can't.

1644
02:07:45,432 --> 02:07:47,692
That kid's long gone.

1645
02:07:48,811 --> 02:07:51,731
This old man is all that's left.

1646
02:07:53,023 --> 02:07:55,403
I gotta live with that.

1647
02:07:55,859 --> 02:07:57,699
Rehabilitated?

1648
02:07:57,736 --> 02:07:59,821
It's just a bullshit word.

1649
02:07:59,822 --> 02:08:04,782
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1650
02:08:06,829 --> 02:08:08,955
Because to tell you the truth,

1651
02:08:08,956 --> 02:08:11,156
I don't give a shit.

1652
02:08:49,580 --> 02:08:51,240
(Gate closes) 

1653
02:09:11,059 --> 02:09:13,259
(Siren passes outside) 

1654
02:09:37,669 --> 02:09:39,749
Here you go, miss.

1655
02:09:41,757 --> 02:09:44,077
Rest room break, boss?

1656
02:09:49,264 --> 02:09:54,769
You don't need to ask me every time you need to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1657
02:09:54,770 --> 02:09:56,310
Yes, sir.

1658
02:10:06,490 --> 02:10:10,190
40 years i've been asking permission to piss.

1659
02:10:10,535 --> 02:10:13,815
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1660
02:10:16,875 --> 02:10:19,675
There's a harsh truth to face.

1661
02:10:20,921 --> 02:10:24,321
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1662
02:10:31,473 --> 02:10:35,833
All I do any more is think of ways to break my parole...

1663
02:10:35,978 --> 02:10:38,838
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1664
02:10:43,568 --> 02:10:46,548
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1665
02:10:47,030 --> 02:10:50,670
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1666
02:10:52,577 --> 02:10:56,414
All I want is to be back where things make sense,

1667
02:10:56,415 --> 02:11:00,115
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1668
02:11:01,795 --> 02:11:04,235
Only one thing stops me.

1669
02:11:04,923 --> 02:11:07,423
A promise I made to Andy.

1670
02:11:27,738 --> 02:11:29,398
Here it is.

1671
02:11:39,624 --> 02:11:41,704
Much obliged, sir.

1672
02:15:04,955 --> 02:15:06,555
(Bird calls) 

1673
02:15:20,512 --> 02:15:21,887
dear red,

1674
02:15:21,888 --> 02:15:24,431
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1675
02:15:24,432 --> 02:15:28,769
And if you've come this far, maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1676
02:15:28,770 --> 02:15:32,470
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1677
02:15:33,650 --> 02:15:35,370
Zihuatanejo.

1678
02:15:36,778 --> 02:15:38,070
I could use a good man

1679
02:15:38,071 --> 02:15:40,197
to help me get my project on wheels.

1680
02:15:40,198 --> 02:15:42,408
I'll keep an eye out for you

1681
02:15:42,409 --> 02:15:44,909
and the chessboard ready.

1682
02:15:45,495 --> 02:15:46,954
Remember, Red,

1683
02:15:46,955 --> 02:15:49,081
hope is a good thing.

1684
02:15:49,082 --> 02:15:51,208
Maybe the best of things.

1685
02:15:51,209 --> 02:15:53,889
And no good thing ever dies.

1686
02:15:54,337 --> 02:15:56,880
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1687
02:15:56,881 --> 02:15:59,008
and finds you well.

1688
02:15:59,009 --> 02:16:01,089
Your friend, Andy.

1689
02:16:36,087 --> 02:16:39,127
get busy living or get busy dying.

1690
02:16:42,469 --> 02:16:44,729
That's goddamn right.

1691
02:16:50,060 --> 02:16:52,269
For the second time in my life,

1692
02:16:52,270 --> 02:16:55,250
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1693
02:16:56,024 --> 02:16:58,044
Parole violation.

1694
02:16:58,109 --> 02:17:02,649
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up any roadblocks for that.

1695
02:17:03,073 --> 02:17:05,199
Not for an old crook like me.

1696
02:17:05,200 --> 02:17:07,880
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1697
02:17:10,997 --> 02:17:16,168
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1698
02:17:16,169 --> 02:17:19,254
I think it's the excitement only a free man can feel.

1699
02:17:19,255 --> 02:17:22,049
A free man at the start of a long journey

1700
02:17:22,050 --> 02:17:24,850
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1701
02:17:27,847 --> 02:17:31,187
I hope I can make it across the border.

1702
02:17:31,893 --> 02:17:35,473
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1703
02:17:37,065 --> 02:17:41,545
I hope the Pacific is as blue as it has been in my dreams.

1704
02:17:43,029 --> 02:17:44,449
I hope.
